nterviews, Chiang reveals the important lessons that Chinese youth learn in their pursuit of elite status. They understand the hierarchy of the status system, recognizing and acquiring the characteristics that are prized, while avoiding those that are not. They maintain status by expecting differential treatment and performing status-based behaviors, which guide their daily interactions with peers, teachers, and parents. Lastly, with the help of resourceful parents, they rely on external assistance in the face of potential obstacles and failures. Chiang looks at how students hone these skills, applying them as they head to colleges and careers around the world, and in their relationships with colleagues and supervisors.Highlighting another facet of China’s rising power, Study Gods announces the arrival of a new generation to the realm of global competition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdolescencezChina. 0aElite (Social sciences)xEducationzChina. 0aSocial statuszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAmerican Teacher.  aAntoine Arnauld.  aArchaeology.  aBra size.  aBrown University.  aCareer.  aCess.  aChinese International School.  aChristian.  aCivilisation (TV series).  aClassroom.  aClimate change.  aClimate.  aCoaching.  aCoimbatore.  aCollege application.  aDeveloped country.  aDiplodocid.  aEducational stage.  aElagabalus.  aElectrical engineering.  aEleventh grade.  aElite Status.  aEmerging technologies.  aEnvironmental determinism.  aEthnography.  aFinding.  aGrader.  aHagiography.  aHellenistic period.  aHukou.  aHumiliation.  aImposition.  aIncome.  aIngredient.  aLanguage barrier.  aLatin honors.  aLausiac History.  aMassif.  aMeasurement.  aMonastery.  aMrs.  aNational Higher Edu